04825nam a22005895i 9780822383208DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20012001ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223832087 a10.1515/97808223832082doi  a(DE-B1597)554041  a(OCoLC)1055058188  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aHIS0410002bisacsh04a972.92/041 aWilliams, James, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Narrative of Events, since the First of August, 1834, by James Williams, an Apprenticed Labourer in Jamaica /cJames Williams; ed. by Diana Paton, Walter D. Mignolo, Irene Silverblatt, Sonia Saldívar-Hull. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (206 p.) :b5 b&w photos, 2 maps, 7 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aA John Hope Franklin Center Book : 3200tFrontmatter -- tAbout the series -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tEditor’s Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tA Note on the Text -- tA narrative of events, since the first of august, 1834, by james williams, an apprenticed labourer in jamaica -- tA report of evidence taken at brown’s-town and st. ann’s bay in the parish of st. ann’s, under a commission from his excellency sir lionel smith, governor of jamaica -- tAdditional Documents -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book brings back into print, for the first time since the 1830s, a text that was central to the transatlantic campaign to fully abolish slavery in Britain’s colonies. James Williams, an eighteen-year-old Jamaican “apprentice” (former slave), came to Britain in 1837 at the instigation of the abolitionist Joseph Sturge. The Narrative he produced there, one of very few autobiographical texts by Caribbean slaves or former slaves, became one of the most powerful abolitionist tools for effecting the immediate end to the system of apprenticeship that had replaced slavery.Describing the hard working conditions on plantations and the harsh treatment of apprentices unjustly incarcerated, Williams argues that apprenticeship actually worsened the conditions of Jamaican ex-slaves: former owners, no longer legally permitted to directly punish their workers, used the Jamaican legal system as a punitive lever against them. Williams’s story documents the collaboration of local magistrates in this practice, wherein apprentices were routinely jailed and beaten for both real and imaginary infractions of the apprenticeship regulations.In addition to the complete text of Williams’s original Narrative, this fully annotated edition includes nineteenth-century responses to the controversy from the British and Jamaican press, as well as extensive testimony from the Commission of Enquiry that heard evidence regarding the Narrative’s claims. These fascinating and revealing documents constitute the largest extant body of direct testimony by Caribbean slaves or apprentices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aApprenticeship programsxGovernment policyzJamaica. 0aSlaveszJamaicaxSocial conditionsy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Caribbean & West Indies / General.2bisacsh1 aMignolo, Walter D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPaton, Diana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSaldívar-Hull, Sonia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSilverblatt, Irene, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822383208zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822383208423Coveruht